title: Birds of 410 Gap Road, Riddells Creek

items.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
items.content_text: Sitting on the window-sill watching its reflection. It let me get VERY close and stayed there for around 5 minutes then flew off. Very beautiful.

items.title: Rhipidura albiscapa
items.content_text: Enjoying what little water is around.

items.title: Rhipidura rufifrons
items.content_text: Taken with iPhone. Very flighty, very beautiful.

items.title: Strepera graculina
items.content_text: This Currawong was seriously upsetting a new holland honeyeater.

items.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
items.content_text: Two kookaburras on the washing line. I'm used to seeing one sitting there but lovely to see two.

items.title: Alisterus scapularis
items.content_text: Ellena Best aged 10 exclaimed "Hey Mum there's a King Parrot!" And sure enough. It is the first time a King Parrot has been recorded on our property. It flew down to the deck and sat on a pole and then sat on the water heater. Its distinctive call could be heard in the surrounding forest.

items.title: Petroica boodang
items.content_text: Seen flying around back garden for three days. Too flighty for me to take a photograph!

items.title: Acanthorhynchus tenuirostris
items.content_text: In a garden-planted Kangaroo Paw.

items.title: Myiagra cyanoleuca
items.content_text: I heard this bird move in at my place just over a year ago but this is the first time caught on camera.

items.title: Acanthorhynchus tenuirostris
items.content_text: In garden-planted Grevillea hybrid.

items.title: Phylidonyris novaehollandiae
items.content_text: In garden-planted Grevillea longistyla.

items.title: Ninox novaeseelandiae
items.content_text: Heard the courtship continuous 'por por por ...' call. First time we've heard this.

items.title: Turnix varius
items.content_text: 3rd pic shows stationary, crouched position when caught in the open with Kookaburras calling as they flew over. Stayed motionless for about a minute.

items.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
items.content_text: Being watched closely by Grey Shrike-thrush.

items.title: Coracina novaehollandiae, Platycercus eximius
items.content_text: Poor photos (long way away) but Cuckoo-shrike is new for my property and Riddells Creek. Gill & I have been hearing a new call for a few days. Rosella has only been recorded once previously at my place too.

items.title: Chalcites lucidus
items.content_text: Flew into window. Placed in bush to recover by Barry Best.

items.title: Aquila audax
items.content_text: Saw it swoop down then up to gradually higher perches. Couldn't see ground but it was disturbed by two kangaroos 30s after swooping down. Perched for 5 minutes.

items.title: Anthochaera carunculata
items.content_text: Nice wattles. In garden-planted Gippsland Waratah (Telopea oreades).

items.title: Podargus strigoides
items.content_text: Male left, female right. They left the roosting spot at 6:18pm. These have been around for a few weeks, heard calling and/or observed on most days on a few roosting spots.

items.title: Strepera graculina
items.content_text: An outbreak of singing by numerous individuals simultaneously, lasted about 5 minutes. Took audio recording.

items.title: Cacomantis flabelliformis
items.content_text: First call of the season. Pre-Spring is here!

items.title: Podargus strigoides
items.content_text: Pair spotted roosting on a dead Blackwood, among Eucalyptus aromaphloia. Second pic shows wing-marks on our window - the birds are feasting on Rain Moths (Hepialidae) on the windows at night at this time of year.

items.title: Solanum laciniatum, Strepera graculina
items.content_text: Ate 8-10 fruit. Initially seen perched in tree and thought it was a Grey Currawong (see pic 2). Pic 3 shows tail feather markings confirming it is the Pied Currawong. Probably moulting.

items.title: Podargus strigoides
items.content_text: Heard banging into windows after rain moths (Hepialidae).

items.title: Phylidonyris novaehollandiae
items.content_text: Washing in bird bath. White-naped Honeyeater flying off in background.

items.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
items.content_text: IDed by call of juvenile. This is the second off-spring this season. Nest is in Eucalyptus viminalis across the road from house.

items.title: Aegotheles cristatus
items.content_text: Recorded call.

items.title: Turnix varius
items.content_text: Single bird on side of road. Walked up to it and it walked into bush and started calling.

items.title: Ninox novaeseelandiae
items.content_text: Calling.

items.title: Acacia melanoxylon, Calyptorhynchus funereus
items.content_text: Four in the Blackwood, Acacia melanoxylon eating seeds - spotted by Gill Best.

items.title: Platycercus eximius
items.content_text: Three birds. This is ony the second time I've seen this species at my place in 12 years. It is thick bush and dominated by Crimson Rosella.

items.title: Podargus strigoides
items.content_text: Flying back and forth towards the windows, chasing Rain Moths (Hepialidae).

items.content_text: Species list for collection.
